\section{In this Study Project}

\secpa

\begin{frame}{In this Study Project}

\begin{itemize}
\item In this study project we investigate new mobility concepts and how it changes the urban infrastructure.
\item The focus is on demand: Which concepts will people use, are people willing to switch mode of transportation and under which conditions.
\item We use economic valuation techniques to answer research questions such as:
\begin{itemize}
\item Which factors facilitate the use of bicycles?
\item Does sharing have the potential to become a key way to organize transportation?
\item Are people willing to pay for better and greener city centers?
\item Are car-free city centers a realistic scenario?
\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Structure of the Project}
\begin{itemize}
\item In the first couple of meetings, we will learn about different mobility concepts, their effects on urban green infrastructures and urban ecosystem services.
\item Further, we explore economic valuation methods, dive into the theory and statistical methods to estimate people's preferences and demand.
\item In small groups, you will investigate potential or existing cases of innovative urban mobility concepts.
\item As the whole group, you conduct your own empirical study.
\item In the excursion week, we visit a European city which has implemented new mobility concepts (e.g., Copenhagen, Amsterdam).
\end{itemize}

\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Educational Objective}

After the project, you should be acquainted with:

\begin{itemize}
\item The role of urban and landscape planning in the development of concepts of urban mobility
\item The interactions between mobility and urban ecosystem services
\item Economic methods to estimate demand in the transportation sector
\end{itemize}

Your skills should have improved in terms of:

\begin{itemize}
\item Holding presentations
\item Writing scientific articles
\item Mastering the many challenges that occur when working in groups
\item Applying economic theory
\item Conducting surveys and collecting data
\item Using statistical methods to estimate preferences and demand.
\item Using R Markdown and \LaTeX
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Case Studies}
\begin{itemize}
    \item In groups of two people, you should investigate an existing case study of new mobility concepts.
    \item Select a broad topic from the following ones:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Public Transportation
        \item Bicycle Infrastructure
        \item Motorized Individual Transport
        \item Integrated Concepts
        \item Sharing Economy
        \item Green Corridors 
        \end{itemize}
    \item Based on the topic chosen, identify an existing case study, preferably in Berlin
    \item Visit the case study area, do a literature research on this case and similar cases, talk with experts and stakeholders... 
\end{itemize}
    
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Case Studies cont.}
\begin{itemize}
    \item Each group member will hold one presentation:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item A summary of the case, with all relevant details and an own evaluation (1 Nov 2018)
        \item Based on the case study, an idea for an empirical research question (29 November 2018).
    
    \end{itemize}
\item Based on the latter presentations, the whole group selects one research idea which we will then put into practice.
\item The whole group will carry out an empirical study using a discrete choice experiment integrated into a survey.
\item Additionally, each group will write an essay on the case study (Alternativ ein Reseach proposal wie ein Antrag).
\end{itemize}
 
\end{frame}

