\section{Discrete Choice Experiments -- A brief introduction}

\secpa

\begin{frame}{Discrete Choice Experiments}

%\begin{center}
Discrete choice experiments are... \pause
\begin{itemize}
\item based on microeconomic theory. \pause
\item a survey based instrument to elicit preferences and willingness to pay values for goods, services or policy changes.\pause
\item a stated preferences approach: The respondent is asked to choose repeatedly between hypothetical alternatives.\pause
\item a tool to investigate several attributes of a good rather than the good itself. \pause
\item an increasingly popular method, especially in trans- and interdisciplinary research. \pause

\end{itemize}
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{The Choice Experiment}


\begin{itemize}

\item A choice experiment consists of... 
\begin{itemize}
\item an introductory text explaining the setting and choice task. \pause
\item a description of each attribute. \pause
\item optionally some reminders e.g. on budget. \pause
\item the choice sets (usually 4 to 12 per respondent).  \pause
\item some follow up questions. \pause
\end{itemize}
\item  A choice set is a set of alternatives, of which the respondent chooses the alternative that she likes most. \pause  


\end{itemize}
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Presentation of the Choice Experiment}


\begin{itemize}
\item Generally, choice sets are presented in matrix form, with the columns representing the alternatives and the rows the attributes. \pause
\item Choice sets can be presented as pictures, maps, simple text. \pause
\item The researcher decides on the number of alternatives and attributes, as well as the values the attributes can take. \pause
\item In some cases, one alternative in a choice set depicts the current situation \textit{as today}. \pause
\item In some other cases, one alternative represents a \textit{no choice} or \textit{opt out}. \pause
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{An example}


\url{https://b1.surveyengine.com/survey/360&preview=true&working=1}

\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Choices made by the researcher}


\begin{itemize}
\item It is not easy to find the proper format to present the choice sets. \pause
\item Each choice comes with advantages and disadvantages.  \pause
\item Some examples of difficult choices for researchers (and respondents): \pause
\begin{itemize}
\item Number of attributes:  More attributes give us more information, but make it more difficult to respondents (recommendation 3 to 7 attributes). \pause
\item Number of alternatives: More alternatives increase the statistical efficiency (as we have more data), but may let the respondent to answer sloppy. \pause
\item Pictures in the choice sets: Using pictures make the choice set look nicer, but may also influence the results or imply a very specific context. \pause 

\end{itemize}
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Some guidance}


\begin{itemize}
\item The valuation scenario should be understood, accepted and viewed as credible by respondents. \pause
\item The valuation scenario should be clearly defined in terms of its spatial and temporal dimensions.  \pause
\item All attributes should be fully defined in scope and size. Respondents have to understand what each attribute means. \pause
\item Attributes should be independent from each other. E.g. ``Biodiversity'' and ``close to nature'' are not independent. \pause
\item The cost attribute should be realistic, credible, familiar and binding for all respondents. \pause
\item The scenario and attributes should be explained as neutral as possible. Avoid priming. \pause 
\item \cite{johnston2017contemporary} provide these and many more important guidance features in great detail. 
\end{itemize}
\end{frame}





